# GOOGL — MoffettNathanson Media Internet & Communications Conference read

_Prepared by earnings-reviewer-from-pdf (offline PDF processing), 2026-05-20. Tier: T1 (BCTK). Source: uploaded conference transcript (FactSet CallStreet PDF, 14-May-2026, 15 pages, YouTube CEO Neal Mohan fireside with Michael Nathanson)._

## 1. Headline read

Neal Mohan (YouTube CEO, not the GOOGL CFO/CEO) sat for a ~40-minute fireside two weeks after the strong 1Q26 print. The signal is **YouTube-specific and thesis-reinforcing, not thesis-changing** — confirms (a) the AVOD→SVOD mix shift continues (Music & Premium >125mm subs, "strongest quarter ever" for non-trial Premium adds in Q1), (b) Living-Room/Connected-TV remains the structural growth engine (>50% of US watch time on TV, 200mm hours/day in US, 1bn hours/day globally), (c) Shorts monetization has reached RPM parity with long-form in the US and "several countries," and (d) the creator-flywheel moat is strengthening as non-endemic talent (Trevor Noah, Oprah, Dwyane Wade, Draymond Green) migrates onto YouTube. Mohan also planted a flag that **"YouTube has decelerated and Search has accelerated"** in the past 12 months — an unusually candid in-house acknowledgment of an ad-mix shift the buyside has been watching, with no quantification or commitment to reaccelerate. Versus the 1Q26 earnings note: this conference reinforces YouTube-flywheel theses but adds a soft drift signal on YouTube ad growth that the PM should track into Q2.

## 2. Strategic themes management emphasized

1. **Creator flywheel is the moat, and it is strengthening, not weakening.** "MrBeast's first rule is YouTube-first" (Mohan, p.9). $100B+ paid to the creator economy over the prior four years. 3mm creators in the YouTube Partner Program monetizing daily. Non-endemic talent (athletes, traditional media celebrities) joining as creators is the new accelerant. Direct quote: "our creators recognize that they have this position of strength now and they can dictate the terms, including having YouTube remain their home" (p.9).
2. **Living-Room / Connected-TV is the structural growth engine.** ">50% of YouTube watch time on TV screens in the US"; "1 billion hours of watch time every single day on living-room devices globally, 200 million in the US"; Shorts watch time on living-room is "one of the fastest growing places" (p.6, p.12). The implicit message: GOOGL is the largest streaming service in the US by watch time, not Netflix. Demographics "across the board" — older viewers growing as fast as young (p.12).
3. **Subscriptions are the second engine, growing faster than ads.** YouTube Music + Premium: >125mm subs. Q1 was "strongest quarter ever in history of Premium globally and also in the US" for non-trial adds (p.4). First Premium price increase in three years was taken just weeks before the conference, with no churn signal flagged. YouTube TV launched 10 specialized tiers ("sports bundle, sports plus news, entertainment, et cetera") — too early to read but framed as TAM-expanding (p.5, p.13). Nathanson explicitly cited subs growing "literally high-teens rates" (p.4) — Mohan did not push back on that characterization.
4. **AI is the empowerment layer across creators, viewers, and monetization.** Gemini/Veo-powered creation tools cut a multi-day editing job to <1 minute. "Ask Studio" inside YouTube Studio for creator analytics. "Ask" feature on viewer side hit 75mm regular users in April alone (p.7). Likeness-detection (analogous to Content ID) being deployed for music — a YouTube-unique capability that gives artists output control over AI-generated voice content. AI slop is "not something you're going to see prevalence of on YouTube" — managed via long-term satisfaction recommendation algorithms (p.8).
5. **Shorts has reached RPM parity with long-form.** "We've reached parity, not just in the US, but in several countries, and in some countries we've even exceeded it, including the US" (p.13). This is a step-up from prior commentary which had framed parity as a goal. Shopping stickers on Shorts driving direct-response; 500k+ creators have tagged videos with shopping (p.13).
6. **Live events as a TAM-expansion and water-cooler moment strategy.** NFL Sunday Ticket framed as TAM-expanding ("you don't need a guy to install a dish on your house"). Multiview innovation cited (originally for sports, now for Coachella). Oscars in 2029. Three-lens framework for live: (1) TAM expansion, (2) tech innovation (multiview), (3) creator enhancement (p.11).

## 3. Forward-looking commentary

- **YouTube TV 10 specialized tiers: too early to call.** "It's really only been launched for a couple months now, so it's still really early, probably too early to say anything concrete about it" (p.13). PM watch item for the next print; Nathanson teed up that the sports-news bundle is not as discounted as he hoped.
- **TPU sales / Cloud capex: not discussed.** This was a YouTube-focused fireside; no hardware or TPU commentary. Do not infer signal on `silicon_architecture_competition` from this conference.
- **YouTube growth deceleration acknowledged, not addressed quantitatively.** Mohan deflected Nathanson's direct question about YouTube ad deceleration vs. Search acceleration into a generic ROI/ROAS framing: "ultimately, all of the ad products that we build... it's about ROI to our advertisers, and that sort of ultimately is what grows the Google Ad business, and of which YouTube also benefits, not just Search over the long run" (p.10). Notable: no commitment that YouTube ad growth reaccelerates; no quantitative target. PM should treat as a soft sandbag — possibly preserving optionality on Q2 commentary.
- **Premium pricing power continues.** First price increase in three years; "despite the price increases over the years, our businesses continue to grow" (p.5). No churn-spike disclosure.
- **Likeness-detection rollout in music.** Capability is live; commercial framing is "artist gets to decide, monetize or remove" — a defensive moat against an AI-music threat the label industry has been worried about (p.8).
- **Consumer ad monetization in Gemini App.** Not discussed at this fireside (consistent with Schindler's "not rushing anything" answer on the 1Q26 call). Conference appearance did not change that posture.
- **Super-aggregator vision (Nathanson Q).** Mohan reaffirmed primetime channels strategy as the answer — "you can get everything from your 15-second Shorts... to 3-hour NFL games, and kind of everything in between" — and noted intent to roll out primetime channels to more countries (p.14).

