## 8. Q&A or fireside-chat flags

1. **YouTube ad deceleration acknowledgment, no commitment to reaccelerate (p.10).** Nathanson asked the most pointed question of the fireside ("over the past 12 months, YouTube has decelerated and Search has accelerated. Talk a bit about the factors..."). Mohan deflected to a generic "Google Ad business" framing and explicitly said "of which YouTube also benefits, not just Search over the long run." This is unusually candid disclosure for a conference fireside. Watch Q2 (2026-07-23) for whether YouTube ad growth reaccelerates or further decelerates relative to Search.
2. **Sandbagging on YouTube TV 10-tier adoption (p.13).** "Too early to say anything concrete." Combined with Nathanson's implicit critique that the sports-news bundle isn't as discounted as he hoped, this signals modest internal hedging on whether the 10-tier strategy is moving the needle on net subscriber adds. Watch Q2/Q3.
3. **Likeness-detection commercial framing was deliberately defensive, not offensive (p.8).** Mohan presented likeness-detection as artist-empowerment (monetize or remove). The strategic question is whether this is also a competitive moat against open-source AI-music tools — Mohan did not address that angle. Likely intentional — message-control vis-à-vis label partners.
4. **Premium pricing power unstressed but not quantified (p.5).** Mohan asserted churn has not increased post-price-hike, but offered no churn data point or attach-rate metric. Standard fireside style, but the absence of any data point is a small flag — operators with strong data tend to share at least one anchor metric.
5. **"AI slop" answer was carefully balanced (p.8).** Mohan acknowledged AI slop is a real risk, said long-term satisfaction algorithms are the defense, then immediately pivoted to "we don't want to overdo that" — protecting Minecraft-streaming-style emergent genres. The pivot is interesting because it signals that recommendation-system aggressiveness against AI-generated content is dialed deliberately conservative. Implication: more AI slop will appear on YouTube than the PR message implies, on the bet that long-term satisfaction signals will sort it.

